course_description: Introduction to the four subfields of anthropology: archaeology, biological anthropology, cultural anthropology, and linguistic anthropology. course_description: This course examines the relationship between culture and personality.  It explores how cultural values, beliefs, and practices shape individual personalities and how personality traits influence cultural patterns.  The course will also consider the impact of globalization and modernization on culture and personality.
metadata: 3 units

course_description: This course provides a broad introduction to the diverse cultures, histories, and societies of Asia.  It examines key themes and issues in Asian studies, such as colonialism, nationalism, globalization, and human rights.  The course will also explore the relationship between Asia and the rest of the world.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: Introduction to biology: Cell structure and function, metabolism, molecular, and organismal genetics, and animal physiology.
metadata: 4 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental concepts and techniques of film analysis.  It explores the history of cinema, different film genres, and the role of film in society.  Students will learn to critically analyze films and to understand the various elements that contribute to their artistic and cultural significance.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental concepts and principles of communication.  It explores various communication models, theories, and contexts, including interpersonal, group, and public communication.  Students will develop their communication skills through active participation in class discussions and activities.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental principles of microeconomics.  It explores the behavior of individual consumers and firms in a market economy.  Topics covered include supply and demand, market structures, consumer choice, and production.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental concepts and principles of literary analysis.  It explores various literary genres, periods, and movements.  Students will develop their critical reading and writing skills through close readings of literary texts.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course provides a broad introduction to the history of the world from prehistory to the present.  It examines key themes and issues in world history, such as the rise and fall of empires, the development of civilizations, and the impact of globalization.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental principles and institutions of American politics.  It explores the history of American political thought, the structure of the American government, and the role of political parties and interest groups.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental concepts and principles of psychology.  It explores various perspectives in psychology, including biological, cognitive, social, and developmental psychology.  Students will learn about research methods in psychology and will apply psychological principles to everyday life.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: This course introduces students to the fundamental concepts and principles of sociology.  It explores various sociological perspectives, including functionalism, conflict theory, and symbolic interactionism.  Students will learn about social institutions, social inequality, and social change.
metadata: 3 units; CSU GE 'B2/B3'

course_description: Introduction to managerial and financial accounting and methods used to record and report managerial and financial information to decision makers internal and external to the firm. Part I.
Introduction to managerial and financial accounting and methods used to record and report managerial and financial information to decision makers internal and external to the firm. Part II.

Accounting process and the application of GAAP to the recognition and measurement of cash, receivables, inventories, property plant and equipment, depreciation and depletion, intangibles, and current liabilities.

Application of GAAP to the recognition and measurement of long-term liabilities, investments, contributed capital, retained earnings, accounting changes and errors, income recognition, accounting for income taxes, pensions, leases, and statement of cash flows.
On-the-job experience in the accounting community. Term paper and meetings with faculty advisor required.

Reading and research of a special area in major under direction of faculty member(s). Project must include statement of objectives, outline of activities planned, results expected, and how they are to be reported and evaluated. Must be approved in advance by the department chair and faculty advisor.

Examines federal income tax concepts, such as gross income, exclusions, deductions, exemptions, and tax credits, especially for sole proprietors. Introduces taxation of property transactions. Development of professional writing skills is integral to this course.
A survey of the general concepts, rules, and practices involved in the taxation of sole-proprietorships, corporations, partnerships, and subchapter S corporations.

Accounting systems analysis, control and design in manual and computerized environments. Knowledge and skills of information technology for auditing AIS systems. Hands-on experience with microcomputers and a computerized accounting system.

Intensive study of areas of law of importance to accountants. Particular attention is given to principles of law relating to contracts, sales, commercial paper, secured transactions, property, legal entities, agency, securities, and accountants legal liability.

Accounting topics relating to consolidation requirements and introduction to the fundamentals of fund accounting, including the general fund, restricted funds, debt service funds, enterprise funds, general long-term account group, general fixed assets accounting group, and accounting entries for encumbrances.
Addresses current issues impacting the accounting profession. Topics vary each semester.

Auditing concepts including standards, objectives and ethics for external auditors. Emphasis on reporting standards, internal control, evidence, statistical sampling, IT audits and assurance. Development of professional writing skills is an integral part of this course.

Theoretical and real life aspects of forensic accounting. Includes discussions of the legal environment, types of forensic engagements such as, lost earnings, business valuations, fraud, and real world forensic cases.

Integration of numerous elements of the accounting program. Current accounting issues discussed. Lectures, discussions, case analysis. (B) managerial-tax-ethics; emphasis on instruction in writing; (C) financial-auditing-accounting information systems.

Integration of numerous elements of the accounting program. Current accounting issues discussed. Lectures, discussions, case analysis. (B) managerial-tax-ethics; emphasis on instruction in writing; (C) financial-auditing-accounting information systems.

course_title: Accounting Capstone: Financial Accounting-Auditing-Accounting Information Systems
course_description: Integration of numerous elements of the accounting program. Current accounting issues discussed. Lectures, discussions, case analysis. (B) managerial-tax-ethics; emphasis on instruction in writing; (C) financial-auditing-accounting information systems.

Auditing and Attestation (AUD) section covers the entire auditing process, including auditing procedures, generally accepted auditing standards, standards related to attest engagements, and the AICPA Code of Professional Conduct.

course_title: CPA Review-The Business Environment and Concepts
course_description: The Business Environment and Concepts (BEC) section focuses on business concepts and the significance of a CPAs professional duties and responsibilities within the larger context of the business environment.
metadata: Grade Option: CR/NC only.

course_title: CPA Review-The Financial Accounting and Reporting
course_description: The (FAR) section focuses on U.S. GAAP, including concepts and standards for financial statements, typical items in financial statements, specific types of transactions and events, accounting and reporting for governmental and other entities.

The Regulation section focuses on federal taxation, especially taxation of business entities; individuals, and property taxation, but also tests on business law, business ethics, and professional and legal responsibilities.

Understanding of complex and critical issues of international corporate governance, financial reporting, and ethical conduct. Includes corporate governance in the U.S., major European markets, and Asia. Emphasis on internal and external stakeholders, regulators, and gatekeepers.

History and theoretical background of accounting standards. Including accounting theories, formulating and testing theories; scientific, pragmatic, syntactic and semantic theories; normative and positive theories. Literature supportive and critical of accounting theories and standards.
Focus on auditing processes, standards, and guidance specific to IT risks. Exposure to advanced IT audit software and its practical application and real world IT audit issues.

Theory and fundamental causes of international variations in accounting. Special emphasis on problems such variations create for financial reporting, control, and decision-making within multinational business enterprises.

In-depth examination of tax and accounting research, IRC, and SEC procedures. Extensive practice in issue identification, reading and analyzing primary authority, and communicating results. Business Administration students only.
Examines advanced topics in federal taxation of partners and partnerships regarding the contribution, operation, and distribution from partnerships and transfers of partnership interests.
Provides the tools necessary for understanding the principles of fiscal accountability and reporting in governmental and not-for-profit organizations.

course_title: Estate and Gift Taxation and Planning
course_description: Examines estate and gift tax provisions and basic estate planning techniques to save taxes and avoid probate. Overviews generation-skipping transfer taxes and income taxes on estates and trusts.
Examines international, state, and local tax issues. Topics include U.S. International taxation of in- and out-bound transactions, sourcing of income and deductions and nexus.

Analyses of a firms profitability, liquidity, and solvency using ratios and common size financial statements. Students are expected to find strengths and weaknesses of the firm based on their analysis.

Introduction to visual analytics. Tableau and Power BI for Excel. Introduction to data processing and blending, data visualization and other visualization techniques. Introduction to PowerQuery, PowerPivot, PowerView, and PowerMap.

Integrates learning through analysis and communication of comprehensive business problems. Stresses research, critical thinking, and analytical and communication skills applied to contemporary accounting and tax issues.
Concentration on current issues impacting the accounting profession. Topics vary each semester.
On-the-job experience in the accounting community. Necessary evaluation reports and meetings with faculty advisor required.
Required for Plan A candidates only; six credit hours required, one must be taken during semester that degree is being awarded.
Provides an overview of financial accounting research. Specific research studies are examined as to their theoretical basis, design, implications, methodology, relevance, etc.

Provides an overview of managerial accounting research. Specific research studies are examined as to their theoretical basis, design, implications, methodology, relevance, etc. PhD students in Business Administration only.

Provides an overview of accounting research in behavioral accounting topics. Specific research studies are examined as to their theoretical basis, design, implications, methodology, relevance, etc. PhD students in Business Administration only.

Provides an overview of accounting research in accounting information systems topics. Specific research studies are examined as to their theoretical basis, design, implications, methodology, relevance, etc. PhD students in Business Administration only.

All students must receive a minimum grade of C in ASL classes in order to continue to the next level. Students with prior experience in ASL are required to take a placement test (email: linguist@hawaii.edu). The placement test is required even if you have had previous ASL courses approved for transfer credits from another institution. The placement exam is strongly recommended if you are interested in taking advanced courses (300-level) and there has been a gap since your last language class, or if you would like a firmer sense of your proper placement. The 101 course is intended for students with no prior experience in the language. If your language proficiency is judged to be beyond the 101-level on the first day of class, you will be placed in a higher-level course. Students who are placed 102 or a higher level may complete the language requirement faster and also earn back-credits (up to 12 credits, which can be counted toward graduation. Restrictions apply: see the Manoa Back Credit Policy at https://manoa.hawaii.edu/ovpae/academic-policies/5-403/). Students starting from 101 will receive no back-credits. A placement adjustment made in the first week of class does not guarantee a seat in the course appropriate for the student.

The minimum required grade for prerequisites is a grade of C (not C-) or better, unless otherwise specified. Sophomore standing or consent is required for all 300-level courses, unless otherwise specified. Junior standing or consent required for all 400-level courses. Graduate standing or consent required for all 600-level courses.
